<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-087-200  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 087 200.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Federal Computer Week  Jan 8 1990 v4 n1 p18(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Rule sets contractor conflict-of-interest standards; OFPP requirescertification of repeated services, use of marketing consultants.andO;(Office of Federal Procurement Policy)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Duffy Marsan, Carolyn.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The OFPP issues a new rule that requires all governmentcontractors of projects worth more than $25,000 to certify thatthey have not violated conflict-of-interest standards.andP;  The ruleapplies to those who provide advisory and assistance services,such as helping an agency design or purchase an automated dataprocessing (ADP) system.andP;  Contractors also have to reveal anyservices provided to agencies within the past year on the same orrelated topic as the contract.andP;  For contractors who win awards ofmore than $200,000, marketing consultants hired during theprocurement process have to be identified.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government ContractsGovernment RegulationConflict of InterestStandardsContractorsCertificationUnited States. Office of Federal Procurement Policy.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>